ident of Columbia University from 1902 to 1945, the longest tenure in its history, expanding the campus and founding Teachers College. His record is also marked by his 1919 introduction of admissions quotas limiting Jewish enrollment.","number":3},{"category":"social_reform","header":"He shared the 1931 Nobel Peace Prize","body":"As head of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, Butler promoted the Kellogg-Briand Pact outlawing aggressive war and in 1931 shared the Nobel Peace Prize with Jane Addams. He advised seven presidents on international affairs.","number":4},{"category":"character","header":"Theodore Roosevelt called him Nicholas Miraculous","body":"A lifelong Republican insider and friend of Theodore Roosevelt, Butler earned the nickname Nicholas Miraculous for his prodigious energy and connections. In 1912 he received the electoral votes meant for Vice President James Sherman, who died days before the election.","number":5}],"burial":{"cemetery_name":"Cedar Lawn Cemetery","city":"Paterson","county":"Passaic","state":"New Jersey","country":"United States"},"education":[{"school_name":"Columbia College","type":"undergraduate","dates":"1882","notes":"A.B. 1882; A.M. 1883; Ph.D. 1884."}],"career":[{"role":"President","organization":"Columbia University","start_year":1902,"end_year":1945},{"role":"President","organization":"Carnegie Endowment for International Peace","start_year":1925,"end_year":1945}],"slug":"nicholas-butler-1862"},"HD2272":{"id":"HD2272","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":9,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00721","mother_id":"HD2270"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1895,"month":7,"city":"Bergen Point","state":"New Jersey"},"death":{"year":1947,"month":2,"city":"England","state":"England"},"gender":"female","ma